<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n18185f"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n18" href="#n18185f">N18 (VI.B.8)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n18all.htm#n18185f"> 185(f)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> bass viol / division viol / lera viol lyre</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">VIOLIN &hellip; The <mark>viol</mark> was made in three main kinds &hellip;. Each of these three kinds admitted of some variation in dimensions, especially the <mark>bass</mark>, of which three distinct sizes ultimately came to be made &mdash; (1) the largest, called the concert bass viol; (2) <mark>the division or solo bass viol</mark>, usually known by its Italian name of viola da gamba; and (3) <mark>the lyra or tablature bass viol</mark>. <small> <a name="EBEB2" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#EBEB2"><cite title="source">Encyclopaedia Britannica</cite></a>, 11th edit. (1911) xxviii 105a</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
